R19-1-245.
Commercial Coercion and Bribery A.
It shall be unlawful for a wholesaler, distiller, vintner, brewer, or importer to induce a retailer to purchase spirituous liquor from the producer or wholesaler to the exclusion, in whole or in part, of spirituous liquor sold or offered for sale by other persons through any of the following means: 1.
By furnishing, giving, renting, lending, or selling to a retail licensee, articles of primary utilitarian value including, but not limited to, the following: clocks, service lamps, ash trays, coasters, napkins, beer mats, book matches, menu cards, folders, meal checks, container mats, back bar mats, thermometers, jiggers, stirring spoons, pouring spoons, glasses, glassware, or any other item potentially useful to the retailer in the conduct of his or her business except as provided elsewhere in these rules.
